```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=record];

    subgraph cluster_0 {
        label="Analog Signal Conditioning";
        color=blue;

        Potentiometer [label="Potentiometer\n(10 kOhms)"];
        Buffer [label="Buffer\n(Op-Amp)"];
        Amplifier [label="Differential Amplifier\n(Op-Amp)"];
        Filter [label="Band-stop Filter\n(50 Hz and 60 Hz)"];
        AntiAlias [label="Anti-Aliasing Filter\n(Low-pass)"];
        LevelShifter [label="Level Shifter"];

        Potentiometer -> Buffer;
        Buffer -> Amplifier;
        Amplifier -> Filter;
        Filter -> AntiAlias;
        AntiAlias -> LevelShifter;
    }

    DAQ [label="Data Acquisition\nSystem (DAQ)", shape=box];

    LevelShifter -> DAQ;
}
```

```Explanations
1. Potentiometer (10 kOhms): The linear potentiometer is the primary sensor used to determine the pendulum's angle. Its resistance varies linearly with the angle of the pendulum. The potentiometer is powered between -10V and 10V, and the voltage at the wiper changes with the angle of rotation from 45 to 135 degrees.

2. Buffer (Op-Amp): A buffer circuit using an operational amplifier provides a high input impedance to prevent loading of the potentiometer and a low output impedance which is necessary for driving the subsequent stages.

3. Differential Amplifier (Op-Amp): This stage is used to scale the potentiometer's output voltage in order to fit within the DAQ's input voltage range of +/-7V. The amplifier will take the buffered signal and amplify it as required to ensure the voltage corresponding to the angle range of 45 to 135 degrees is mapped correctly to the input range of the DAQ.

4. Band-stop Filter (50 Hz and 60 Hz): Due to the specification that frequencies around 50 and 60 Hz should be attenuated, a band-stop filter (also known as a notch filter) is included. This filter is designed to attenuate unwanted interference from power line noise, which is common in many environments.

5. Anti-Aliasing Filter (Low-pass): Prior to sampling by the DAQ, an anti-aliasing filter is essential to prevent higher frequencies (above the Nyquist frequency, which is half the sampling rate) from aliasing into the frequency band of interest. Given the DAQ's sampling rate of 1000 samples per second, a low-pass filter with a cutoff frequency slightly below 500 Hz will be suitable.

6. Level Shifter: This block is used to adjust the DC level of the signal if necessary so that the signal range is centered around 0V and fits within the +/-7V input range of the DAQ without clipping.

7. Data Acquisition System (DAQ): This is the system that receives the conditioned analog signal and samples it at the specified rate of 1000 samples per second. The DAQ is only responsible for acquiring the signal; it cannot be altered or tuned, thus necessitating the above signal conditioning steps.
```

